{#n130}
Dugdale's Baronage, vol. i. p. 784. Brady's hist. vol. ii. App. No 92. The pay of a man at arms was quadruple. We may therefore conclude, that the numerous armies, mentioned by historians in those times, consisted chiefly of ragamuffins, who followed the camp, and lived by plunder. [p:Edward]'s army before [l:Calais] consisted of 31,094 men; yet its pay for sixteen months was only 127,201 pounds. [Brady, ibid.]

{#n131}
Commodities seem to have risen since the Conquest. Instead of being ten times cheaper than at present, they were in the age of [p:Edward III]. only three or four times. This change seems to have taken place in a great measure since [p:Edward I]. The allowance granted by [p:Edward III]. to the earl of [l:Murray], then a prisoner in [l:Nottingham] castle, is one pound a week; whereas the bishop of [l:St. Andrews], the primate of [l:Scotland], had only six-pence a day allowed him by [p:Edward I].

