Fortescue, who, soon after this period, visited [l:France], in the train of prince [p:Henry], speaks of that kingdom as a desert in comparison of [l:England]. See his Treatise _de laudibus Angliæ._ Though we make allowance for the partialities of Fortescue, there must have been some foundation for his account; and these destructive wars are the most likely reason to be assigned for the difference remarked by this author.

